      <hedline>
        <hl1>Credit to the Novelist</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Tom C Smith letter praises Bill Desowitz for Dec 12 (1999) article on male characterizations in film (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Kudos to Mr. Desowitz for pulling together so well the powerful theme (male awakening) which strings together ''Fight Club,''  ''American Beauty,''  ''Bringing Out the Dead'' and ''Magnolia.'' I couldn't agree more with his dead-on analysis of these films, especially ''Fight Club,'' for which Mr. Desowitz rightfully applauds the director, David Fincher.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Kudos to Mr. Desowitz for pulling together so well the powerful theme (male awakening) which strings together ''Fight Club,''  ''American Beauty,''  ''Bringing Out the Dead'' and ''Magnolia.'' I couldn't agree more with his dead-on analysis of these films, especially ''Fight Club,'' for which Mr. Desowitz rightfully applauds the director, David Fincher.</p>
        <p>It should be noted, however, that while Mr. Fincher's images are masterly, the concepts, situations and most of the razor-sharp dialogue in the film are all based on the brilliant novel (same title) by Chuck Palahniuk.</p>
        <p>TOM C. SMITH  Wallingford, Conn.</p>
        <p>MEN IN FILMS</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
